[25] Divisions and of Pt IIA of the Code . Following a verdict of not guilty because of mental impairment at a special hearing by judge and jury in the Supreme Court of the Northern Territory ("the Court") conducted under Div of Pt IIA of the Code,[] s X() of the Code requires the Court to either declare that the accused person is liable to supervision under Pt IIA, Div of the Code or order that they be released unconditionally. A declaration is an "order" within the meaning of Pt IIA, Div.[] As such an order, ss ZM and ZN apply to the making of the declaration. Section ZM provides:

[26] "In determining whether to make an order under this Part, the court must apply the principle that restrictions on a supervised person's freedom and personal autonomy are to be kept to the minimum that is consistent with maintaining and protecting the safety of the community." . Section ZN provides:

[27] "() In determining whether to make an order under this Part, the court must have regard to the following matters: (a) whether the accused person or supervised person concerned is likely to, or would if released be likely to, endanger himself or herself or another person because of his or her mental impairment, condition or disability; (b) the need to protect people from danger; (c) the nature of the mental impairment, condition or disability; (d) the relationship between the mental impairment, condition or disability and the offending conduct; (e) whether there are adequate resources available for the treatment and support of the supervised person in the community; (f) whether the accused person or supervised person is complying or is likely to comply with the conditions of the supervision order; (g) any other matters the court considers relevant. () The court must not make an order under this Part releasing a supervised person from custody (whether conditionally or otherwise) or significantly reducing the supervision to which a supervised person is subject unless: (a) the court has: (i) obtained and considered reports, each report being prepared by a person who is a psychiatrist or other expert (but the same person must not prepare both reports); and

[28] (ii) considered the reports submitted to the court under sections ZJ and ZK and received by the court under section ZL, if any; and (b) subject to subsections () and (), the court is satisfied that each of the following persons was given reasonable notice of the proceedings concerned: (i) the victim of the offence concerned;

[29] (ii) if the victim concerned is deceased – the victim's next of kin;
